{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4e052019-22a1-44cc-9acd-2402d3886acb","content":"You're using **MSTest 3.8.2** on .NET 9.0, which fully supports constructor injection. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n**Constructor** → sync init + `TestContext` injection  \n**`[TestInitialize]`** → async init (runs before each test)\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private readonly MyService _service;\n    private DbConnection _connection;\n\n    // Sync init: constructor injection for TestContext\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        _service = new MyService();\n    }\n\n    // Async init: runs before each test\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _connection = await _service.ConnectAsync();\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Connection established\");\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public async Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        await _connection.DisposeAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        var result = await _connection.QueryAsync(\"...\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(result);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for MSTest 3.x:**\n\n- **Constructor injection** replaces the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern.\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** can return `Task` for async work — no need for `.Result` or `.GetAwaiter()`.\n- Use **`[ClassInitialize]`** / **`[ClassCleanup]`** (static) for one-time setup shared across all tests in the class.\n- Constructor runs per-test, just like `[TestInitialize]`, but only for **synchronous** setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5b878b39-27d2-4ae4-9da1-4b747e8713a8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has MSTest 3.8.2 targeting .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), `TestContext` can be injected via the constructor. Let me provide the recommended pattern for both synchronous and asynchronous initialization.\n\nIn MSTest v3+, the recommended approach is:\n1. Constructor injection for `TestContext` (instead of the old property-based approach)\n2. Use the constructor for synchronous initialization\n3. Implement `IAsyncInitialization` or use `[TestInitialize]` for async initialization\n\nActually, let me be more precise. In MSTest 3.x:\n\n\n- `TestContext` gets injected through the constructor\n- `[TestInitialize]` methods can be async and return `Task`\n- `[ClassInitialize]` methods can also be async\n\nSo the pattern I'd recommend is using the constructor to receive `TestContext` and handle any synchronous setup, then using an async `[TestInitialize]` method for any async initialization work.","outputTokens":668,"requestId":"A034:3665CC:41D7052:461B421:6A034CD9"},"id":"aef1cc1a-c9b4-43b0-9f67-6fbd678f595f","timestamp":"2026-05-12T15:53:10.836Z","parentId":"f4631e9b-99d6-440b-aad1-ba1d7edf533f"}
